	abstract = {A model of anisotropic magnetogasdynamic turbulence is developed in order to investigate quantitatively a turbulent fluid origin for the small spatial scale density fluctuations observed in 1981 by Armstrong, Cordes, and Rickett in the interstellar medium. The anisotropy at these small spatial scales is not a free parameter, but results from the presence of a large-scale approximately uniform magnetic field that is a sum of the steadystate galactic magnetic field and the large-scale turbulent magnetic field fluctuations. The observed density fluctuations are interpreted to be two-dimensional isobaric entropy variations with oppositely directed gradients in temperature and density projected transverse to the local approximately uniform magnetic field. The observed distribution of the electron density variations is produced by the convection and distortion of these dynamically passive entropy fluctuations by the turbulent velocity and magnetic field fluctuations. In this work I investigate the nature of small-scale turbulent velocity and magnetic field variations that drive the density variations in the presence of a strong local magnetic field. Developing a model based on a significant new (1982) study of Montgomery, it is found that the small-scale turbulent velocity and magnetic fluctuations are distributed anisotropically and are concentrated transverse to the local magnetic field. In these directions transverse to the local field, transport coefficients are dramatically decreased compared to the transport coefficients found in the absence of magnetic fields. The energy-conserving inertial ranges of the modeled anisotropic flows, whose structures at small spatial scales are controlled by viscous damping, extend to significantly smaller spatial scales than the inertial ranges of isotropic turbulent flows. Thus, the power required to maintain an inertial range to small spatial scales is dramatically decreased by the use of these models of anisotropic turbulence. In order to quantify the properties of the modeled turbulent flows, three possible sites—cloud shell H ii regions, diffuse H n regions produced by O stars, and the tenuous intercloud medium—were investigated as possible locations for turbulent flows. It is shown in the H n sites that the energy-conserving inertial ranges of the modeled flows can extend to dimensions of an order of magnitude smaller than the smallest spatial scale observed by Armstrong, Cordes, and Rickett. The convection and distortion of entropy fluctuations and the possible contribution of magnetoacoustic waves are addressed in future works.},
